Title:
Brute Ratel v1.1 “Stoffel’s Escape” Release (Badger core rewrite & evasion upgrades)

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This release post describes Brute Ratel C4 v1.1 updates, centered on a full rewrite of the “Badger” implant core to reduce memory artifacts and known IOCs highlighted by public reverse-engineering/detection writeups.  
- It replaces prior reflective-DLL-centric design elements with a new staged/wrapper approach, adds per-build randomized crypto keys, and introduces polymorphic shellcode generation (e.g., random register usage) to resist signature/YARA detections.  
- Major in-memory evasion changes include on-demand DLL loading, PEB-based module discovery to avoid LoadLibrary/LdrLoadDll, proxying DLL-load calls via legitimate Windows functions to evade EDR stack-tracing/EtwTI-based heuristics, and expanded sleep masking with full-region encryption plus thread stack masquerading/start-address spoofing.  
- It expands indirect syscall support to x86 and WOW64, adds “phantom_thread” (alertable-thread context hijack with ROP gadget redirection), and introduces “memhook” for runtime patching/hooking of arbitrary memory regions without BOFs.  
- Operational features include built-in SOCKS with nested pivoting, “burnable” SOCKS profiles, SOCKS over DoH, improved staging (small ~7–8KB stages) and exit behaviors for APC/QAPC scenarios, plus various Commander UX/tasking improvements.  
- Useful primarily for red teams/pentesters and adversary emulation operators; also relevant to blue teams for understanding modern C2 implant evasion patterns and telemetry gaps.

Technical Focus:
- Indirect syscalls (x64/x86/WOW64) and syscall-based evasion
- PEB module enumeration and DLL-load proxying (LoadLibrary/LdrLoadDll avoidance)
- Sleep masking, full-region in-memory encryption, custom heap/zeroization
- Thread stack masquerading, start-address spoofing, APC/QAPC execution nuances
- Alertable-thread injection via context hijacking + ROP gadgets (“phantom_thread”)
- Pivoting via built-in SOCKS, SOCKS over DNS-over-HTTPS (DoH)

Use Cases:
- EDR-evasion-focused implant deployment and post-exploitation on Windows
- Stealthier process injection and thread-based execution (alertable thread targeting)
- Nested pivoting inside segmented networks (SMB/TCP pivots, SOCKS/DoH routing)
- Runtime patching of security controls or program behavior via in-memory hooks
- Blue-team detection engineering: hunting for PEB-walking, proxied DLL loads, stack-masqueraded threads, and indirect-syscall patterns

Keywords:
